Implement scaled dot-product multi-head self-attention from scratch in PURE Python (only the `math` module; no numpy/torch). Define exactly:

    def multihead_attention(x, w_q, w_k, w_v, w_o, n_heads, causal=False):

`x` is a list of token vectors (list[list[float]], shape [seq, d_model]). `w_q,w_k,w_v,w_o` are each d_model x d_model matrices (list[list[float]]). Compute Q=x@w_q, K=x@w_k, V=x@w_v; split the d_model columns into `n_heads` contiguous heads of size d_head=d_model//n_heads; per head do scaled dot-product attention with factor 1/sqrt(d_head); if causal=True, position i may attend only to positions j<=i; softmax each attention row; concat heads back to d_model; project through w_o. Return list[list[float]] of shape [seq, d_model]. Respond with ONE Python code block.

Implement nucleus + top-k logit filtering in PURE Python (`math` only). Define exactly:

    def topk_topp_filter(logits, top_k, top_p):

Return a Python set of token indices (into the original `logits` list) that survive filtering: (1) if top_k>0, first restrict to the top_k highest-logit indices; (2) compute softmax over the surviving logits; (3) keep the smallest set of highest-probability tokens whose cumulative probability is >= top_p (the nucleus), always keeping at least the single highest-probability token even if its prob already exceeds top_p. Ties broken by higher logit then lower index. Respond with ONE Python code block.

Implement grouped-query-attention KV-head expansion in pure Python. Define exactly:

    def repeat_kv(kv, n_rep):

`kv` is nested lists of shape [n_kv_heads, seq, head_dim]. Return shape [n_kv_heads*n_rep, seq, head_dim] where each kv head is repeated `n_rep` times CONTIGUOUSLY: input head h maps to output heads [h*n_rep, h*n_rep+1, ..., h*n_rep+n_rep-1] (the standard GQA memory layout). If n_rep==1 return an equivalent structure. Do not mutate the input. Respond with ONE Python code block.

Implement Rotary Position Embedding (RoPE) for a single vector in pure Python (`math`). Define exactly:

    def apply_rope(vec, pos, base=10000.0):

`vec` has even length d. Use the half-split convention: split into x1=vec[:d//2], x2=vec[d//2:]; for i in 0..d/2-1 use angle theta = pos / (base ** (2*i/d)); rotate the pair (x1[i], x2[i]): out1[i]=x1[i]*cos(theta)-x2[i]*sin(theta); out2[i]=x1[i]*sin(theta)+x2[i]*cos(theta); return out1+out2 (length d). pos=0 must return vec unchanged. Respond with ONE Python code block.

Implement a bounded thread pipeline in pure Python (threading + queue only). Define exactly:

    def run_pipeline(items, n_workers, process):

Distribute `items` (a list) across `n_workers` worker threads using a BOUNDED queue (queue.Queue(maxsize=max(1, n_workers*2))). Each worker pulls items and applies `process(item)`. Collect every result and return them as a list IN THE SAME ORDER as `items`. Shut down cleanly with sentinels (no busy-wait, no deadlock, no lost or duplicated results). Must work for len(items) >> n_workers. Respond with ONE Python code block.

Write a thread-safe generic LRU cache in Rust (std only). Public API:

    pub struct LruCache<K, V> { /* ... */ }
    impl<K: std::hash::Hash + Eq + Clone, V: Clone> LruCache<K, V> {
        pub fn new(capacity: usize) -> Self;
        pub fn get(&self, k: &K) -> Option<V>;
        pub fn put(&self, k: K, v: V);
    }

Both get and put take &self (interior mutability via Mutex). On capacity overflow, evict the least-recently-used entry. get and put are O(1) amortized and update recency. It must be Sync (usable behind Arc across threads). Must compile as a library (`rustc --edition 2021 --crate-type lib`). Respond with ONE Rust code block.

Write, in Rust (std only), a custom iterator type yielding overlapping windows over a slice (like slice::windows, but your own type). Required:

    pub struct Windows<'a, T> { /* ... */ }
    impl<'a, T> Windows<'a, T> {
        pub fn new(slice: &'a [T], size: usize) -> Self; // panic if size == 0
    }
    impl<'a, T> Iterator for Windows<'a, T> {
        type Item = &'a [T];
        fn next(&mut self) -> Option<Self::Item>;
    }

Each call to next yields the next length-`size` contiguous sub-slice, advancing by one element; returns None when fewer than `size` elements remain. Lifetimes must be correct. Must compile with `rustc --edition 2021 --crate-type lib`. Respond with ONE Rust code block.

Write a bounded multi-producer single-consumer channel in Rust using ONLY std (Arc, Mutex, Condvar, VecDeque). Required:

    pub fn channel<T>(capacity: usize) -> (Sender<T>, Receiver<T>);
    pub struct Sender<T> { /* Clone */ }
    pub struct Receiver<T> { /* ... */ }
    impl<T> Sender<T> { pub fn send(&self, value: T); }      // blocks while full
    impl<T> Receiver<T> { pub fn recv(&self) -> Option<T>; } // blocks while empty; None once all senders dropped AND buffer empty

`Sender` is Clone (multi-producer) and tracks the live sender count so the receiver can detect close. Use Condvars to block/wake (no busy-wait). Must compile with `rustc --edition 2021 --crate-type lib`. Respond with ONE Rust code block.

The following Rust does not compile. Identify the bug in ONE sentence, then provide the corrected version as the LAST code block. It must compile with `rustc --edition 2021 --crate-type lib` and preserve the intent: return the longest whitespace-separated word in the input together with its byte length.

```rust
fn longest_word(text: &String) -> (&str, usize) {
    let mut best = "";
    for w in text.split_whitespace() {
        if w.len() > best.len() {
            best = w;
        }
    }
    let owned = String::from(best);
    (&owned, best.len())
}
```

Implement a CSV pivot in pure Python. Define exactly:

    def pivot(rows_csv):

`rows_csv` is a CSV string whose first line is the header `region,product,amount` (amount is an integer; no quoted fields). Return a nested dict {region: {product: total_amount}} summing `amount` across all matching (region, product) rows. Skip blank lines. Use only stdlib (the `csv` module is fine). Respond with ONE Python code block.

Implement a line-based diff in pure Python WITHOUT using difflib. Define exactly:

    def unified_diff(a, b):

Compute the longest-common-subsequence of the lines of `a` and `b` (split on '\n'), then return a single string (lines joined by '\n') where: unchanged lines are prefixed with a single space ' '; lines only in `a` are prefixed with '-'; lines only in `b` are prefixed with '+'; ordering must be a valid diff (you can reconstruct `a` by reading the ' ' and '-' lines in order, and `b` by reading the ' ' and '+' lines in order). Implement the LCS yourself (dynamic programming). Respond with ONE Python code block.
